title: test 8pm 11/24
content:
Nice catch—this screenshot actually explains what’s going on.

In GitHub Desktop you’ve got this in the top bar:

Pull origin with 1 ↑ 2 ↓

That means:

1 local commit ahead of GitHub (your “Added admin project list…” commit)

2 commits behind GitHub (there are 2 commits on GitHub that you haven’t pulled yet)

Because you’re behind, Desktop is telling you to pull first before it will let you push.

What to do

In GitHub Desktop (MBEngineering-main repo):

Click the blue “Pull origin” button.

Let it finish the pull:

If there are no conflicts, it will just fast-forward or merge.

After a successful pull:

The button should change to “Push origin” (you’ll probably see 1 ↑ 0 ↓ or 0 ↑ 0 ↓ if it auto-pushed).

Click “Push origin” if it doesn’t auto-push.

Go back to your GitHub repo page in the browser and refresh:

You should now see your new commit, something like
Added admin project list with thumbnail + edit support.

Quick sanity check

If you want to double-check in Desktop:

Click the History tab.

You should see your recent commit at the top of the local history.

Once you’ve pulled and pushed, the same commit will appear on GitHub’s history page too.

Do that pull → push sequence and your admin changes (project list + editing) will be live in the remote repo.
